CUSTOMER SEGMENTATION¶

What is customer segmentation all about¶

Customer Segmentation is process of dividing customers into different groups based on common features so companies can well position their products and services in the market for each of the discovered groups in the data.

What is the goal of the project ?¶

This project aims at analyzing the data from a store's database which lists purchases made by 2000 customers. I developed clustering models that recognized customer groups based on customer income and age.

What is the data ?¶

2000 customer purchases from a store's database.

Unsupervised Learning Techniques¶

Hierarchical Clustering¶

Hierarchical clustering is an unsupervised learning model used to group data by similarity with a dendrogram. It is an easy method to find the clusters in the data.

In [15]:
hier_clust = linkage(seg_std, method = 'ward')
In [16]:
plt.figure(figsize = (12,9))
plt.title('Hierarchical Clustering Dendrogram')
plt.xlabel('Observations')
plt.ylabel('Distance')
dendrogram(hier_clust,
           truncate_mode = 'level',
           p = 5,
           show_leaf_counts = False,
           no_labels = True,
           color_threshold = 0)
plt.show()

Finding the clusters¶

Find the longest vertical line form the dendrogram that intercepted by a horizontal line.This is where we make the cut and form the clusters. All we need to now is to remove the color threshold

In [17]:
# An easy way to identify the clusters is to take out the color threshold
plt.figure(figsize = (12,9))
plt.title('Hierarchical Clustering Dendrogram')
plt.xlabel('Observations')
plt.ylabel('Distance')
dendrogram(hier_clust,
           truncate_mode = 'level',
           p = 5,
           show_leaf_counts = False,
           no_labels = True)
plt.show()

We have 4 clusters in the dataset.

1. Cluster 1 = Green
2. Cluster 2 = Red
3. Cluster 3 = Light Blue
4. Cluster 4 = Purple

This clustering method is not very efficient with large datasets but its advantage is it finds the clusters in the data. So one can start with the hierarchical technique to discover the clusters and the Flat clustering techniques(K-means) for segmentation.

K-Means Clustering¶

what it means¶
How K-means works.¶
  1. choose number of k
  2. specify cluster seeds
  3. Assign each of the points to a seed
  4. Calculate the centroid or the geometrical center

Disadvantage

  1. sensitive to outliers
  2. picking the clusters before hand
  3. k-means enforces spherical clusters

Determining the optimal number of clusters¶

In [18]:
# within cluster sum of squares
wcss=[]
for i in range (1,11): 
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters= i, init='k-means++', random_state = 42)
    kmeans.fit(seg_std)
    wcss.append(kmeans.inertia_)

We already know that we have 4 clusters in the data but we could check just to be sure by trying different clusters.

In [19]:
plt.figure(figsize = (12,9))
plt.plot(range(1,11), wcss, marker = 'o', linestyle = '--')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('WCSS')
plt.title('The Elbow Method showing the optimal k')
Out[19]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'The Elbow Method showing the optimal k')

The Elbow method is what would be used to pick the right number of clusters. Clearly, we can observe the elbow at 4. This result agrees with the results from the dendogram so we would use 4 clusters.

We can fit both clusters and analyze the results.

Interpretation¶

  1. Comfortable - Customers in this cluster are equally male and female, non single and are the oldest cluster of the groups. They are well educated people who earn about 160,000 dollars on average. They also are skilled workers and self employed individuals, who live in medium and large cities.
  2. Fewer-oppurtunities- People in there 30's about 1% of them are in relationships and male, receive low income and live in smaller cities.
  3. Career Focused - Male customers who are not in relationships in their 30's too. They are skilled and self employed individuals who earn about 142,000 dollars and live in large and medium cities.
  4. Standard - Comprised of female customers who are in a relationship also well educated, skilled workers with high income and live in small cities.

Cluster 4 takes the biggest share in the data followed by career focused. Now that we have a fair understanding of who the customers are we can start developing strategies on who to reach the needs of each of the groups.

Principal Component Analysis¶

Principle component analysis creates as many components as in the data and they are arranged in levels of importance, i.e how much of the variability in the data is explained by each component

In [30]:
pca = PCA()
pca.fit(seg_std)
Out[30]:
PCA(copy=True, iterated_power='auto', n_components=None, random_state=None,
    svd_solver='auto', tol=0.0, whiten=False)
In [31]:
pca.explained_variance_ratio_
Out[31]:
array([0.35696328, 0.26250923, 0.18821114, 0.0755775 , 0.05716512,
       0.03954794, 0.02002579])

From the above output, you can observe that the principal component 1 holds 35.7.2% of the information while the principal component 2 holds only 26.3% of the information. Also, the other point to note is that while projecting dimension some information would be lost.

In [32]:
# picking the best components
plt.figure(figsize=(12,9))
plt.plot(range(1,8),pca.explained_variance_ratio_.cumsum(), marker = 'o', linestyle='--')
plt.title('Explained Variance by Components')
plt.xlabel('Number of Componets')
plt.ylabel('Cumulative Explained Variance')
Out[32]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Cumulative Explained Variance')

Interpretation¶

The rule of thump is to preserve 70 to 80% of the variance, so we would use 3 principle components.
